    <AT-descriptions>
      <AT-description lang="en">The 'Mangroves of Western Indian Ocean' is a regional ecosystem subgroup (level 4 unit of the IUCN Global Ecosystem Typology) that includes intertidal forest and shrublands of the marine ecoregions of Cargados Carajos/Tromelin Island (Western Indian Ocean province), Delagoa (Western Indian Ocean province), Mascarene Islands (Western Indian Ocean province), Seychelles (Western Indian Ocean province), Southeast Madagascar (Western Indian Ocean province), East African Coral Coast (Western Indian Ocean province), Northern Monsoon Current Coast (Western Indian Ocean province), Bight of Sofala/Swamp Coast (Western Indian Ocean province), Western and Northern Madagascar (Western Indian Ocean province). The biota is characterised by 17 species of true mangroves and other key plant taxa that provide structure and resources for approx. 370 mangove-associated taxa. Mangroves in this subgroup have a mapped extent of at least ... km2 in ... countries and are predominantly ... and .... They are threatened by  conversion for urban and tourism development, agriculture and aquaculture, and by increases in frequency of tropical storms. </AT-description>
    </AT-descriptions>
